Given that the survey was conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it follows the change of attitude in the region.
Two elements are the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the relatively sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes toward democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6 percent per year since 2002, support for democracy has gone from a minimum of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, reducing the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44 percent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase of 25 per cent in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34 percent said they had confidence in the European Parliament in their countries and 45 percent in their government, the same as last year, in both cases, but in a strong increase compared to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent respectively).
